*************************
Nissan Motors=E2=80=99 Likely End
*************************

In late December 2024, Nissan announced a plan to merge with Honda. Well, t=
hey are calling it a merger. But it is more like a takeover. A shotgun marr=
iage hastily arranged by the Japanese government to save a spiraling compan=
y left behind by the times. Again. Nissan's story has been up and down, up =
and down. But this latest ride down looks to finally be the end. In this vi=
deo, a look at Nissan's tumble back down the stairs.

----------
Beginnings
----------

In 1999, Carlos Ghosn was Renault=E2=80=99s number two executive and a risi=
ng star. He joined Renault from the tire company Michelin in 1996 at a time=
 of great turmoil. That year, Renault turned a $926 million fiscal loss. Bu=
t thanks to aggressive cost cutting and a lineup of new cars, the state-own=
ed company swung to a $1 billion profit in 1998. Now Ghosn or "Le Cost Kill=
er" was asked to join Nissan as its new COO and turn it around. In May 1999=
, Renault agreed to invest 5 billion euros into the struggling Japanese car=
maker for 36.8% of Nissan's shares, with a future option for more later. Ye=
ars of excessive global expansion, foreign assimilation, and lackadaisical =
management had left Nissan with uneconomical factories (just 53% utilizatio=
n), a crappy lineup (just 4 lines out of 40+ were profitable) and unproduct=
ive workers. The move was met with great skepticism. People thought Nissan =
was done. And when it sank, Renault would sink with it. One London analyst =
insisted, "Nissan probably shouldn't even be in the auto business".

--------------
Le Cost Killer
--------------

Over the next two years, Ghosn and his team of 40 French executives ruthles=
sly cut costs and paid off debt. Many of these changes broke the norms of h=
ow Nissan previously did business, but can be justified on the basis of a f=
inancial crisis. First, the Renault team simplified the company's complicat=
ed portfolio of cross stock holdings. Nissan was holding the stocks of 1,30=
0 companies just because they were part of the same business family, or Kei=
retsu. Second, the team halved the company's sprawling web of suppliers. Ma=
ny had been charging Nissan inflated prices, again just because they were "=
family". Relationship managers were assigned to get the best price, family =
or not. Such efforts have real benefits, and yielded at least $2.25 billion=
 in savings. Third, the Renault team shook up the employee incentive struct=
ure. Ghosn broke norms by elevating various younger people over peers who w=
ould otherwise received those positions on the basis of seniority. Finally,=
 and perhaps most appallingly from a Japanese cultural perspective, his Nis=
san revival plan cuts 21,000 jobs through attrition and shuts down five fac=
tories. Such a thing, routine in the United States, was vexing to the Japan=
ese. Yet it can be argued that cuts were needed to shake off the cruft. For=
 instance, Nissan appointed many former senior managers to be "advisors" or=
 "coordinators", ghost jobs with no operational authority but often hindere=
d progress. Those were gone. As a carrot to soothe wounded egos, Ghosn play=
s to Nissan's greatest hits by bringing back classic cars like the Z-series=
 and the GT-R. Moreover, nobody in Japan could deny the financial results. =
In 2002, Nissan returned to profitability, ahead of schedule.

-------------
Continuing On
-------------

Ghosn's success and unique background brought him fame beyond that of the b=
usiness world. He was lauded by his peers, named Industry Leader of the Yea=
r by Automotive News for three straight years. The Japanese even famously m=
ade a manga about him. And other carmakers wanted him to come save them too=
. In the 2000s, Ford and General Motors fell into crisis and the government=
 had to issue emergency loans to two of them. Steve Rattner - appointed by =
the US government to be its point man, the so-called Car Czar - tried to re=
cruit Ghosn to run General Motors. Imagine how Ghosn's star would have rise=
n even further had that happened! But he turned it down. In 2002, Renault r=
aised its stake in Nissan to 43%. And Nissan acquired a 15% stake in Renaul=
t, though without the equivalent voting capacity. Three years later in 2005=
, Ghosn became Renault's CEO without needing to step down from his current =
position at Nissan. Things at Nissan were looking good. They hit their 2002=
 three-year plan's goals by selling a million more cars per year, while mai=
ntaining strong operating margins of 10%. Such good performance was lifted =
by a good US market - lots of Pathfinder SUVs and Altima passenger cars. At=
 a press conference, Ghosn declared Nissan's recovery from crisis complete.=
 Yet he had apparently felt that there was more work to be done at the comb=
ined companies, to grow them further. He immediately declared another 3-yea=
r plan, the "value up", to add yet another million cars in annual sales.

-----
China
-----

Core to Ghosn's growth strategy was tapping the booming Chinese automotive =
market. In 2000, Nissan set up a joint venture between itself, a state-owne=
d car maker called Dongfeng Motor, and two other car companies. The JV was =
called Fengshen Auto (=E9=A2=A8=E7=A5=9E, or "wind god"). Fengshen was basi=
cally a local assembly operation, producing Chinese variants of Nissan's po=
pular Bluebird car with technical help from a Taiwanese company called Yulo=
n. Fengshen acquired a factory from its JV partner and produced 2 billion R=
MB of profits. This success prompted the Chinese government to desire a dee=
per partnership. So Ghosn traveled to Mainland China in 2001, and in Septem=
ber of the following year negotiated a 50-50 partnership producing passenge=
r cars, trucks and the like. The new JV got off to a rocky start. Fengshen =
was a fast moving Chinese organization with important pricing decisions som=
etimes made in as soon as an hour. The goal was to mate that with Nissan's =
technology prowess. But the initial setup had things in reverse. Chinese wo=
rkers were in charge of production, and the Japanese were in charge of sale=
s. A 10% sales decrease in 2004 forced these problems to be rectified in a =
restructured constitution that aligned the teams to their proper order. In =
2005, Dongfeng Nissan's sales exploded 160%, making it the fastest growing =
carmaker in China that year. And they remained a top-10 carmaker in China f=
or the next few years after other major JVs like those backed by VW and GM.

--------------
Looming Clouds
--------------

Throughout the 2000s, Nissan faced major short and long term challenges. In=
 the short term, there was the Global Financial Crisis. Sales fell 22% and =
the company turned a $2.9 billion net loss in 2009. They were forced to cut=
 thousands of jobs. And then there was the devastating March 2011 earthquak=
e, which damaged factories and halted global supply chains. Nissan and the =
rest of the Japanese car industry worked around the clock to get back on tr=
ack. In the backdrop of all of this, there were major long term industry-wi=
de developments that Ghosn correctly saw as upending the whole industry. I =
point to the famous 2015 presentation by former Fiat Chrysler CEO Sergio Ma=
rchionne: "Confessions of a Capital Junkie", which lays it all out pretty w=
ell. In the presentation, Marchionne wrote about the effects of rising R&D =
costs to meet ever-tightening safety and environmental regulations. More mi=
les per gallon of gasoline. New safety equipment. Stronger car bodies, but =
light ones too. Because of the mpg. All this means higher fixed costs of ca=
r development - Marchionne's estimate was $132 billion in 2014 - which in t=
urn means needing to sell a lot more cars for a good return. Moreover, the =
high proportion of fixed costs causes big swings in profitability as sales =
fluctuate. The interesting thing is that about less than half of those deve=
lopment costs are for things customers do not differentiate on like those s=
afety features. Carmaker consolidation can help share those costs and save =
money for the things that customers actually do care about. The carmakers t=
hat can get big enough are the ones that will survive. The well-connected C=
arlos Ghosn correctly foresaw all of this. He also rightfully believed that=
 the Renault-Nissan alliance - with its six million annual units sold - had=
 the potential to compete with VW, Toyota or GM. His production goal for th=
e two seemed to have been about 10 million cars a year. So in 2011, he told=
 reporters that Nissan's latest plan - its longest yet - would raise global=
 market share from 5.8% to 8% while also raising operating margins. This wo=
uld be achieved in part by selling more into Japan, China and the United St=
ates, where Nissan hoped to grow their share to 10% by 2017.

----------------
Unhealthy Growth
----------------

These were difficult targets, and the company sought to achieve them in sev=
eral, arguably unhealthy ways. First, they started offering deep discounts =
on their cars and for a long time thereafter. By 2018, Nissan incentives av=
eraged 16.7% according to JD Power, higher than the industry's 10%. They al=
so structured their dealer incentives to favor very aggressive sales. A par=
ticularly popular one was a "stair step" incentive. If dealers hit ambitiou=
s sales quotas, they get nice cash bonuses. If they fall short, they get no=
thing. Internally they called it "grow or go". This all-or-nothing arrangem=
ent worked fine at the beginning when sales quotas were relatively reachabl=
e. But as quotas repeatedly ratcheted up, bonuses got rarer and dealers got=
 desperate or disgruntled. Many left altogether. Another arguably unhealthy=
 long-term sales strategy was selling more to rental fleets. Rental car cus=
tomers rack up big miles on a car before selling it into the used car marke=
t. These fleets are large, so it can disrupt the car models' resale value f=
or everyone else. These actions reek of "growth at all costs". It trashed b=
rand value, annoyed dealers and worried consumers.

--------------------
Missed Opportunities
--------------------

Moreover, the company's lineup started to stagnate. The late 2000s and earl=
y 2010s saw American tastes shift towards SUVs and trucks in part due to ch=
eaper gas costs. And once again, Nissan's core sedan lines fell out of favo=
r. In response, they introduced a few, high potential products that had the=
 right idea in mind but eventually fizzled out. There was the Nissan Titan =
pickup truck - introduced in 2003 as a direct challenge to Ford and GM's co=
re profit centers. But Nissan found it tough to manufacture, the truck's lo=
ok went stale, and sales fell short of Ghosn's public annual sales targets =
of 100,000. There was the Nissan Leaf. It was an EV pioneer, and Ghosn tout=
ed it for many years. And Ghosn was even super early to self-driving, sayin=
g in 2013 that Nissan cars would be able to drive themselves by 2020. EVs a=
nd self-driving are winning ideas so it turns out. But Nissan's execution w=
as lacking, leading to missed opportunities. For example, while Nissan was =
developing the Nissan Leaf, Renault was developing their own EV too: the ZO=
E. The two cars had almost nothing in common. Even the battery - over which=
 the two teams could not come to terms on. So the idea was apparently to le=
t the two duke it out in the market. The issue was later rectified but the =
resulting cars were too expensive for the general consumer, leading to lost=
 time and momentum.

------------------
Simmering Tensions
------------------

As I mentioned, Ghosn and his management correctly saw that consolidation w=
as needed. In 2005, the two companies worked together only in purchasing. B=
ut Ghosn strove for closer ties, particularly in manufacturing. In 2008 for=
 instance, the two companies worked together hand in hand to build a plant =
in India. Now in the wake of the 2011 announcement, he pushed his engineers=
 to work even more closely. Ghosn cut individual budgets to force them to c=
ollaborate, and named managers with responsibilities in both companies. He =
also wanted 70% of the Alliance's cars made from one of three platforms by =
2020 - compacts, minivans, and midsized vehicles. This was called the Renau=
lt-Nissan Common Module Family, which enabled cars like the successful Niss=
an Rogue compact SUV. But attempts like these ran into troubles, touching t=
he simmering cultural and geopolitical tensions inside the Alliance. Car en=
gineers bristle at these sorts of things. Can't blame them for it. It sort =
of feels soulless. A former Japanese union leader was quoted in the New Yor=
k Times saying:

The powertrain, then the transmission. Then it was the next thing and then =
the next thing, until it got to a place where the car=E2=80=99s identity wa=
s at stake. Some people started asking: =E2=80=98Isn=E2=80=99t that going m=
uch too far?=E2=80=99

And then there was what Nissan perceived as its uneven arrangement, where t=
he smaller Renault had voting power over Nissan but not vice versa. And tha=
t Nissan was increasingly propping up the other company. Nissan did not bel=
ieve a partnership could be a true partnership until this can be fixed. But=
 Renault saw this shareholding arrangement as a matter of contract. And sin=
ce both companies were so tight with their governments, such tensions had g=
eopolitical concerns. Famously in 2015, the French government raised its st=
ake in Renault, which threatened Nissan. This led to a kerfuffle and a face=
-saving agreement that the French government would not interfere in Nissan'=
s operations.

-------------------
Ghosn the Celebrity
-------------------

And there were the problems with Ghosn himself. As so famously said, you di=
e a hero or live long enough to see yourself become the villain. Ghosn ran =
Nissan for a very long time. And after nearly twenty years, he had cemented=
 himself into the company with a handpicked board and no credible successor=
s. Particularly after being made CEO of Renault in 2005, Ghosn grew a taste=
 for the jet-setting life: Buying art, investing in wineries, and hanging w=
ith the elite bigwigs at Davos. You need some good pay to fund such a lifes=
tyle, and the issue with that was that Ghosn was already being paid a lot. =
At least in the context of Nissan being a Japanese company. In 2010, he was=
 reported to have made $9.6 million in cash and stock. Just to compare, the=
 next highest paid Nissan executive that year made $2.2 million. Akio Toyod=
a, Toyota's chairman, made just $1.4 million. A salary about as good as a d=
ecent AI researcher, so it turns out. Though definitely true he is part of =
the founding family. Even Howard Stringer, the Welsh-American CEO of Sony, =
made just $4.5 million that year. Which, to be clear, is life-changing mone=
y for anyone including me. Unless of course you are the type to rent out Ve=
rsailles for your wedding.

-----------------
Arrest and Escape
-----------------

Ghosn's pay disputes, his perhaps overstayed tenure, his lifestyle, and the=
 tensions over a forced merger eventually led to his downfall. The proximat=
e cause behind the whole fiasco was the discovery by internal auditors that=
 residences in Lebanon and Brazil had been purchased by Nissan for Ghosn's =
personal use. Unusually, the internal team that discovered these went strai=
ght to law enforcement to discuss them. Nissan's board was not informed and=
 didn't know about this until the news broke. In November 2018, Carlos Ghos=
n and a top deputy was lured to Japan on the pretense of a high-level meeti=
ng. Then he was arrested, stripped of his positions, and charged with under=
reporting his income by some 5 billion yen over five years. Several other c=
harges were later added. Ghosn claimed innocence and was eventually release=
d on bail. A year later, he flees Japan to Lebanon in a daring escape - whe=
re he was apparently hidden inside a musical equipment box? He settled in L=
ebanon, claiming that he was fleeing a rigged justice system. And unfortuna=
tely the two Americans who helped smuggle him out of the country were arres=
ted in the US, extradited to Japan, and jailed for 1-2 years. They claimed =
that Ghosn had misled them. The SEC alleged that Ghosn and his team at Niss=
an worked to raise his compensation by up to $140 million and conceal that =
fact. All three settled and paid nominal fines in 2019 to settle the allega=
tions. Good times all around.

----------
Post-Ghosn
----------

As I mentioned, Ghosn was a critical connector within the company, and his =
abrupt departure threw things into a loop. Even more so when his immediate =
successor as Nissan CEO Hiroto Saikawa then had to resign when it came out =
that he himself had violated internal rules about his stock pay. From 2019 =
to 2021, Nissan struggled to regain itself after the excesses of the Ghosn =
era amidst a pandemic. They cut more jobs, closed a few more factories abro=
ad, dialed down the incentives and fleet sales, and they reset their relati=
ons with their dealers. For that, they took a sizable loss of revenue thoug=
h that has since come back. Another major reset Nissan wanted was to reset =
its unequal shareholding relationship with Renault. Such a deal took a whil=
e - filled all over with toxicity, leaks to the press, massive internal inf=
ighting, and tangled ties to disentangle. The final deal was sealed in 2023=
 after Nissan forced out its COO and two of its directors, which stridently=
 objected to the deal. This deal trimmed Renault's stake in Nissan to 15% b=
y selling some shares and putting others into a trust. Nissan gained voting=
 rights for the 15% that it held in Renault. And in exchange, Nissan will b=
uy into Renault's new EV division Ampere. This thing is complicated. And I =
haven't even mentioned Mitsubishi Motors up until now! That awkward third c=
hild bolted on in 2016 after a major emissions scandal. They=E2=80=99ve bee=
n hanging around since, their future cloudy. At the announcement, Nissan's =
CEO Makoto Uchida said:

This alliance has gone through a lot=E2=80=89 ... =E2=80=89but the past is =
the past. We had to debate about the future ... For me, China was a wake-up=
 call and we also face a massive challenge in terms of rolling out electric=
 vehicles in the US

Speaking of which ...

---------------
Rise of the EVs
---------------

I don't think anyone could have anticipated that the Chinese EV natives wou=
ld come up as fast and aggressively as they did. These Chinese EV companies=
 develop, make and sell cars like if they are consumer electronics. Fueled =
by a powerful EV ecosystem and a titanic domestic market that allowed for t=
rue economies of scale, these Chinese EV companies can produce incredible p=
roducts at hyper speed. I think the example of Xiaomi's entrance into the E=
V market perfectly illustrates this. What does a company more known for pho=
nes know about the joy of driving, purists might ask. Yet just three years =
after declaring their entrance into the market in 2021, Xiaomi has brought =
out some amazing cars. Xiaomi's car puts together scaled components pioneer=
ed by BYD, Huawei and CATL to get the performance. And in so many colors! T=
hen to achieve customer differentiation, they put their HyperOS operating s=
ystem into the car. This lets them integrate the car into their ecosystem, =
which already includes things as varied as blenders, microphones, humidifie=
rs, and projectors. Xiaomi claims that their SU7 SUV seamlessly connects wi=
th 1,000 different gadgets. It also somewhat justifies Xiaomi's selling the=
 car at below cost. The Chinese EV industry spits fire like none other, and=
 it is one of the most formidable class of tech products to ever emerge fro=
m anywhere. The old guard Chinese internal combustion engine joint ventures=
 like Dongfeng Nissan got rolled as they struggled to keep up. In 2023, Nis=
san's Chinese sales fell some 30%. Similar declines are projected for 2024.=
 The utilization at their seven factories in China is said to be 50%. China=
 makes up a third of Nissan's sales, it is basically their top market. And =
while this is not a Nissan specific thing - Honda and Toyota are fighting h=
ard there too - it certainly does not help that senior management was tousl=
ing with itself and Renault on a share deal as it happened. Fiddling while =
Rome burns. And now the management chaos will presumably go on for years as=
 merger talks with Honda go forth.

----------
Conclusion
----------

Before we conclude, I want to thank the user known as Vyetic for inspiring =
this video. Though it came out way later than I thought it would. The news =
have been pretty clear that the Honda-Nissan talks were initiated when word=
 got out that the Taiwanese giant Foxconn began sniffing around Renault or =
those trust banks, thinking about buying into Nissan. Foxconn has been chas=
ing the EV industry for a while, looking to enable a client to break into t=
he United States and the rest of the world. They tried Lordstown and Fisker=
, with little effect. Nissan would be the ultimate play. And I reckon Foxco=
nn can make a good EV. They helped on the Luxgen n7 SUV, and I find it a fi=
ne automobile. The issue is that Foxconn hasn't had the best time running S=
harp, and Nissan is one of Japan Inc's crown jewels. Thus the abrupt tieup =
with Honda. But Honda is not super stoked about dealing with Nissan's probl=
ems. Which include an aging lineup and a lopsided cost situation where Japa=
n accounts for less than 20% of car production but almost half of the workf=
orce. Infamously, Honda's CEO was asked at the press conference why Nissan =
would make a good business partner for Honda and he said "That's a difficul=
t one". Honda wants Nissan to triple its profit by 2026 to pass a test for =
the merger to continue, putting the onus on Nissan to try and save itself. =
But if they can do that, then why merge? Anyway, the whole thing is a ragin=
g dumpster fire. I think there's a decent chance the merger happens. After =
that ... who knows? Whether it happens or doesn=E2=80=99t happen, either ca=
se, the end of Nissan as an independent entity approaches.

